To derive the given string from the start-symbol ​S the grammar must use the only rule for S:

S → NT33 NT75

Hence the string must be the concatenation of two blocks:
• a block generated by NT33
• immediately followed by a block generated by NT75.

The non-terminal NT75 can be expanded in only two ways:

1. NT75 → 't262' | 't249' | 't224'          (a single terminal token)
2. NT75 → NT61 NT0                          (two non-terminals)

If option 1 were used, the string would have to contain one of the tokens t262, t249 or t224 as its very last symbol, because nothing can follow the single token produced by NT75.  
The given string ends with “… t55 t328 t47”, so option 1 is impossible.

For option 2, the first symbol produced by NT75 is whatever NT61 can generate.  
NT61, however, is defined only by the five terminal rules

NT61 → 't296' | 't356' | 't320' | 't305' | 't26'

Hence the first symbol in the NT75 block must be one of  
t296, t356, t320, t305, t26.  
None of these terminals appears anywhere in the given 21-token string, so option 2 is also impossible.

Since NT75 cannot generate any substring of the given string, S cannot derive the whole string, and thus the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

In every derivation the start symbol S first expands as  
S → NT33 NT75.  
The left-most token of any generated string therefore must be produced by NT33.

NT33 can either  

1. produce a single terminal (t187, t220, t58) – none is t267, or  
2. expand as NT33 → NT40 NT101, in which case the first token comes from NT40.

NT40 in turn can only start with  

• the terminal t355 (not t267), or  
• NT40 → NT62 NT41, so the first token is generated by NT62.

NT62 may  

a) produce one of the terminals t6 or t201 (neither is t267), or  
b) expand as NT62 → NT1 NT67 (first token from NT1), or  
c) expand as NT62 → NT3 NT10 (first token from NT3).

Tracing each of these possibilities:

• NT1 can start with one of the terminals t373, t319, t177 or with NT55 … – no possibility yields t267.  
• NT3 can start with the terminal t39 or with NT14 … – again, none of the ensuing productions lead to the terminal t267.  

Consequently, under every possible expansion of NT33 the first token produced is never t267.  
Since the given string begins with t267, it cannot be generated by NT33, and therefore cannot be generated by S.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
